The Telegram direct session is pinned to `github-models/openai/gpt-4.1`.\n- That model is rejecting the request before the reply starts with: `413 Request body too large for gpt-4.1 model. Max size: 8000 tokens.`\n\nWhat’s happening:\n- Your injected startup/system/workspace context is bigger than what that `gpt-4.1` route accepts.\n- So even a tiny Telegram message like `Hi` fails immediately.\n- OpenClaw is surfacing a generic “context limit exceeded / reset conversation” fallback, which is the bad part.\n\nEvidence I checked:\n- `openclaw status` → Telegram channel state: `OK`\n- Telegram session files show repeated:\n  - `errorMessage: \"413 Request body too large for gpt-4.1 model. Max size: 8000 tokens.\"`\n\nFastest fix:\n- Stop using `github-models/openai/gpt-4.1` for that Telegram session.\n- Switch Telegram/main session model back to a route with a larger effective prompt budget, ideally your default `openai-codex/gpt-5.4`, or another model/provider that accepts the full injected prompt.\n\nSecondary issue:\n- The session index currently points Telegram direct to a missing session file once, which suggests some session-reset/state mismatch too, but the primary blocker is still the 8k request-body cap on that model.\n\nIf you want, I can now inspect exactly where that Telegram model override is being set and tell you the minimal safe change needed without touching anything yet.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_073bb756a6496b760169ce7b172c1c8191bcb850cf801bb755\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":2742,"output":470,"cacheRead":31744,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34956,"cost":{"input":0.006855000000000001,"output":0.00705,"cacheRead":0.007936,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.021841}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775139598107}}
